item.title: Metals Inch Higher Despite Demand Uncertainty
item.description: Base metals and gold made solid gains as the dollar eased back, but with the greenback generally remaining strong, BMI said it saw little scope for a strong rise in prices in the coming months.

item.title: Dollar Falls on Month-End Profit Taking; Data to Test Investor Sentiment
item.description: The dollar fell on month-end profit taking and as Treasury yields retreated from high levels, but the currency’s “underlying strength” has not been reversed, with the DXY dollar index still trading around 106, UniCredit Research said.

item.title: Crude Oil Tempers Gains Amid Strong Monthly Rise
item.description: Crude oil prices inched higher in Europe, with the recent rally tempered late Thursday over worries that oil had become overbought, ING said.

item.title: China Proposes Easing of Cross-Border Data Controls
item.description: The country’s cyberspace regulator has proposed the easing of cross-border data-security controls in a bid to boost business activities within the country.

item.title: Nikkei Ends Flat as Auto, Financial Stocks Weigh
item.description: The Nikkei Stock Average closed flat at 31857.62 as losses in auto and financial stocks offset gains in chip stocks.

item.title: U.K. Economic Growth Revised Higher
item.description: U.K. GDP expanded 0.2% in the second quarter, matching preliminary estimates, but growth in the first three months of the year was revised up, indicating the economy could be withstanding some of the pressures from high inflation.

item.title: Poland's Culture Wars Snare Oscar-Nominated Director Agnieszka Holland
item.description: As parliamentary elections in mid-October near, government leaders say a movie about a recent refugee crisis tarnishes the country.

item.title: Suicide Ignites Debate Over Protecting Teachers
item.description: In South Korea, the death of a first-grade teacher in an elite school district has fueled protests over student protections put in place over the past decade.

item.title: Reserve Bank of Australia Set to Extend Rate Pause But Retain Hawkish Hue
item.description: The Reserve Bank of Australia is widely expected to leave its official cash rate on hold for a fourth month on Tuesday.

item.title: Kevin McCarthy Wins Three, Loses One in Late-Night Spending Votes
item.description: House Republicans largely succeeded in passing a series of annual spending bills, trying to show that the conference can stay united on legislation headed into any negotiations with Democrats to avert a shutdown.

item.title: The BM-21 Is Obsolete and Prone to Breakdown, but Ukraine Wants More
item.description: The BM-21 rocket launcher—like at least two-thirds of Ukraine’s arsenal—is from the Soviet era. WSJ explains how it works and why Ukraine is trying to get more, despite it being outdated and imprecise.

item.title: EVAN GERSHKOVICH | DETAINED FOR 6 MONTHS
item.description: Our colleague Evan was detained six months ago while reporting in Russia. He has been held in Moscow on an espionage charge that the Journal and the U.S. government vehemently deny.
